==English==
=== Etymology ===
From Middle English, ''mysterie'', from Latinized {{Gr.}} ''mysterium'', from [[Ancient Greek]] '''[[μυστήριον]]''' (''mysterion'') "a mystery, a secret, a secret rite", from '''[[μύστης]]''' (''mystes'') "one initiated", from '''[[μυάω]]''' (''myao'') "to compress the lips", from '''[[μυώ]]''' (''myo'') "to close, to be shut".

=== Noun ===
'''mystery''' (plural '''mysteries''')
# something [[secret]] or unexplainable; [[unknown]]
#*The truth behind the events remains a '''mystery'''.
# with an [[obscure]] or puzzling nature
#*That man is a '''mystery'''.
# a truth that needs [[divine]] [[revelation]]
#*The story of [[Jesus Christ]] remains a [[religious]] '''mystery''' in many ways.
# a [[particular]] [[sequence]] of events in the life of [[Jesus|Christ]]
# a secret [[society]] [[initiation]]
#* Both John Kerry and George Bush were members of [[:w:Skull and Bones|Skull and Bones]] with a '''mystery''' [[initiation]] process not yet [[revealed]].

